description.text:
UPDATE: Posted version 3 which adds "total_minx", "total_maxx", "total_miny" and "total_maxy" as well as similar dims for each layer named "layername_minx" and so on. UPDATE: Posted version 2 which works well in both Inkscape version 0.91 and 0.48. Most of us have our favorite tools. One of mine is Inkscape. I'm no pro but I've been able to do what I need with it. Another of my favorites is OpenSCAD. The purpose of this thing is to make it easier to take something from Inkscape and use it in OpenSCAD. The current steps you need to take to turn an SVG into an OpenSCAD usable DXF are the following:

  • Convert all objects to paths

  • Add extra points to paths

  • Convert paths to lines

  • Export to DXF
    • After all that you may use your SVG design in OpenSCAD, but then if you want to edit your design you are faced with two equally unpalatable options: edit the original design and go through the steps again, or edit the DXF directly. I had had enough and set out to automate that process. I took all the best parts of at least 3 other DXF output extensions (I lost count!) and added automation for the steps listed above. With this Inkscape extension, you can edit/save your design and simply "Save a Copy As" to DXF whenever you want to try it in OpenSCAD. It is a lot smoother that way. Supposedly it exports color to the dxf as well but I don't know if that's supported in openscad. NOTE: If you change the size of the document in Inkscape the exported DXF will have misplaced objects. A workaround for this is to recreate all layers after resizing the document. I know, painful, but once you have the size worked out it's not bad. BONUS FEATURE: The extension automatically adds dimensions to the DXF: layer_name_width and layer_name_height for each layer and total_width and total_height. The dimensions can be accessed using the built-in dxf_dim command. Ex.: total_width = dxf_dim(file = "openscaddxf.dxf", name = "total_width"); Three fairly small provisos:

  • It's fairly slow because it has to launch a new inkscape instance to convert the objects to paths. It's not a pretty solution, but I believe it's the only way to do it at the moment.

  • Doesn't work with groups. You will need to ungroup everything before exporting

  • Doesn't work with intersecting lines. This will cause either the offending objects to disappear or everything will appear outlined instead of filled in.
    • Repo is here: https://github.com/brad/Inkscape-OpenSCAD-DXF-Export

Copy the "openscad_dxf" folder and openscad_dxf.inx file (the zip contains these files) to your Inkscape extensions folder: http://wiki.inkscape.org/wiki/index.php/Script_extensions#Installing Alternatively, if you have pip and want to try an even easier (but experimental) installation method you can try using pip install --target=<installation_dir> inkscape-openscad-dxf. If you do use this method, do not use a ~ to refer to your home directory. Some versions of pip will misinterpret it and create a directory called ~ in the current directory. Create some objects in Inkscape and save them directly to a DXF that OpenSCAD can use! The included STL is an extruded DXF generated from pure Inkscape objects. Enjoy!

description.text:
Mounting bracket for small PCB type USB B ports.  
I made this as I couldn't find a USB B female port suited for mounting on my mendelmax. Seriously, I looked everywhere for a plug that would suit the mounting holes provided.

parts required:
  • four 3mm (of suitable length) bolts for mounting, with nuts and washers
  • USB B PC mount socket (e.g. http://www.jaycar.com.au/productView.asp?ID=PS0920), with mounting PCB.
    • Print the bracket The USB B port is soldered onto the small PCB that was provided with it, along with a 4x2.54mm set of male pins, for connecting the cable from the control board (I used a RUMBA, which has suitable pins for connecting to the USB). The PCB is mounted on the bracket. using two of the bolts. The bracket is mounted on your printer using the other two 3mm bolts. Connect the to the usb port to the printer board using a 4 pin female-female cable (may require some testing to get the pin order correct, if you don't have the schematics for your plug and board).

A direct drive NEMA17, bowden, mk8 extruder design that attaches to 15by15 openbeam.
I've had some issues with existing extruder designs, namely that the pushfitting have been pushed through the plastic threads or come out of alignment, causing the filament to jam. Or simply that there was not enough pressure on the idler.
This desing attempts to fix those issues by clamping the pushfitting to an m5 nut and using leveraged tension on the idler.
I also wanted to be able to adjust the idler tension as well as being able to clean the hobbed gear without having to take the extruder apart.
Its a bit fiddly to put together but once assembled it does the job without a hitch!

Edit: I've uploaded a new scad-file which is now parametric in regards to hobbed gear. Just enter the inner diameter of your hobbed gear as per http://reprap.org/wiki/Drive-gear

There is also experimental support for flexible filament guides. I've added selectable guides to the scad-file but I haven't printed them yet!

description.text: A model of the MAKE robot for animation. You can make this shell and have a poseable MAKE robot or you can make the insides as well and have an animated MAKE robot. It's large size 24cm tall leaves plenty of room inside for the workings. A movie and a STEP CAD file are available in the downloads.

I used my UP 3D printer with default settings and white ABS. For prolonged use I would recommend using bigger servos, mine were small 9gram ones and they do struggle a bit to move the arms.  
Print the two legs and front body section, they should just fit together. Mine clipped together without the need for glue, but you can glue them together if necessary.  
Next print the arms and arm pins, glue the pins into the arms through the body, if you want the model poseable or animated make sure you don't glue the arm to the body, also if you want to animate it, put some grease in the body arm hole to ensure free arm movement.  
Lastly print the rear body and head. This should be all that is necessary for a poseable model.  
To make it animated, print the servo bracket, servo gears and head coupling. Mount 3x9gram micro servos with a single arm servo horn each in the bracket, fit the gears to the servo horns. I glued mine on. Connect it up to your chosen microcontroller. I have included Arduino code in the downloads that you can use, look for the .ino file.  
The insides picture shows the layout of the internals, the white part is the front of the body, the dark grey are the arms and legs, the green is the servo bracket, the orange are the arm servo gears and the pink are the arm pins. I glued the servo horns to the arm gears to make them nice and solid, there is a hole in the gear so you can still get the gear and horn off the servo. I also had to velcro strap the servos into the bracket as they were moving around too much.  
I plan to power the robot with 6 AA batteries, 3 in each leg, I also want to mount an on/off switch. There should be loads of room for the arduino and breadboard inside.

description.text:
Remix del Robottino Android.
Aggiunti dei led ad alta luminosita negli occhi,attivati da un microswitch posto sulla testa ed alimentato da due pile ministilo AAA (con resistenza in serie per abbassare la corrente e aumentare la durata).
Ho modificato l'alloggio delle pile aggiungendo una pila aggiuntiva (i led ad alta luminosità necessitano di un'alimentazione dai 3,18 ai 3,3 V),raggiungendo così un alimentazione di 4,5 V. Come si vede dalla figura del circuito la corrente assorbita dai led è di 1,32 mA,mentre la caduta di tensione sulle resistenze porta ai capi del led una tensione di funzionamento di 3,18 V (in linea con i valori del led,evitando cosi di bruciarlo)
Nell'incasso a C creato nel blocco piedi va inserita una lamella di contatto per unire elettricamente i poli delle due pile e nel foro all'estremità va fatto passare il collegamento del polo negativo,mentre nella parte superiore vanno inserite delle molle o delle lamelle di contatto per creare i due poli + e - dell'alimentazione.

description.text:
Modified the original bracket for use on a Skywatcher 200P reflector. Stepper motor is the Nema17-PG27 with a flexible coupler. It is for use with a myFocuserPro I've built.

Bolt hole spacings needed changing as did the height of the platform for the stepper motor. Printed easily in PLA, but I wanted to use ABS, which warped badly when printed standing on its edge. So I made back face of the bracket flush the whole length so it can be printed with this side down. This solved the warping issue, but obviously uses more material.

The stepper has all been installed using 20mm M3 bolts and washers, and fits well. Yet to actually run the focuser though. An immediate improvement could be curving the mating surface with the scope.

  • removable / adjustable camera plate
  • design incorporates a feet for easy storage
  • weight swivels to compensate for an unbalanced camera
  • air bubble for leveling the camera
  • adjustable handle position with a screw thread which allows for very fine adjustments of the center of mass
  • light weight design
    • This project originated from the urge to create tools that help designers create professional results in times of budget cuts. It supports smooth and professional moving video footage. It is created from a single sheet of laser-cut material, making it easy for any student to create and assemble. This open-source project cuts costs for such a professional tool and makes it accessible for every student / diy'er. We love to see your own Stead i Cam so upload a picture of it!

description.text: Made this in 3DS Max.

The Mmintbox is my design for an enclosure for an Arduino with an LCD keypad shield. These are the files for my latest prototype. This version of the case will work with LCD keypad shields from DFRobot, Sainsmart, and most of the generic ones from eBay.
The case has supports built in to handle the overhangs, so no support material is necessary.
I used the button mold to make button pads from Oogoo: http://www.instructables.com/id/How-To-Make-Your-Own-Sugru-Substitute/

title: Marlin Firmware for Max Micron dual head & auto levelling Prusa i3

description.text:
This is the Firmware directly from Max Micron used for the Dual Head & Auto Levelling printer. So you can reflash your printer with a custom Marlin based on the original. I myself used it to enable the EEPROM.
Better instructions for compiling and flashing the printer done!

Firmware pour l'imprimante "Dual Head & Auto Levelling" de chez Max Micron. Si tout comme moi vous avez besoin du firmware de base afin de faire des modifications. J'en avais besoin pour pouvoir activer l'EEPROM sur la mienne.
Meilleurs instructions pour la compilation et le flashing de l'imprimante en ligne!

Easy, I send an email to Max Micron asking for their Marlin firmware for these printer and tada :)

Facile, j'ai envoyé un email à Max Micron leur demandant si je pouvais avoir le firmware Marlin de cette imprimante et tada :)

You can download the zip with the EEPROM already activated (and go to the compiling/flashing part) or take the other one and follow these instructions.

These instructions are especially made for the Dual Head & Auto Level printer from Max Micron with the official custom Marlin firmware from Max Micron. The steps are similar for other printers but some details could change!

Download the Arduino IDE

Download and install the IDE from Arduino to edit the Firmware:
https://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software
(available on all systems)

Edit Configuration.h file

Open the Configuration.h file with Arduino. It'll open all files from the firmware so check if your on the good one.

Find and uncomment the following lines by deleting the slash (lines 556 and 559):
//#define EEPROM_SETTINGS
//#define EEPROM_CHITCHAT

Build the firmware and flash your printer

Compiling the firmware

Before compiling you have to choose the correct board. To do those open the menu Tools -> Board and choose "Arduino Mega 2560". This is the one mostly used in 3D printers and for our printer aswell.

Then you can compile the firmware by going in Sketch -> Verify / Compile

Flashing the printer

First you have to connect your printer if it's still not. Now you have to choose in which USB port you plugged it in Tools -> Serial port. This is the tricky part, there's no way (at least I don't know one) to be sure to correctly choose. You might try and see if it work.

Finally you can flash the printer by selecting Sketch -> Upload

Télécharger la version avec l'EEPROM déjà activé (et voir la partie compiler/flasher) ou prendre l'autre zip et suivre les instructions.

Attention, ces instructions concerne l'imprimante Dual Head & Auto Level de Max Micron avec le firmware Marlin personnalisé officiel de Max Micron. Bien que les étapes soient similaire à d'autres imprimantes certains détails peuvent être différent!

Télécharger l'IDE Arduino

Télécharger et installer l'IDE Arduino pour pouvoir éditer le firmware
https://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software
(Disponible pour tous les systèmes)

Ouvrir le fichier Configuration.h

Ouvrir le fichier Configuration.h avec Arduino. Vérifier de bien être dans le bon fichier car Arduino va probablement ouvrir tout les fichier du firmware.

Trouver et décommenter les lignes suivante en enlever les 2 slash (lignes 556 et 559):
//#define EEPROM_SETTINGS
//#define EEPROM_CHITCHAT

Compiler le firmware puis flasher l'imprimante

Compiler le firmware

Avant de compiler il faut choisir la bonne carte. Pour se faire ouvrir le menu Outils -> Board et choisir "Arduino Mega 2560". C'est le carte la plus utilisée pour les imprimantes 3D et c'est celle que la notre embarque.

Ensuite vous pouvez compiler le firmware en allant dans Croquis -> Vérifier / Compiler

Flasher l'imprimante

Premièrement si ce n'est déjà fait, connecter l'imprimante à votre ordinateur. Maintenant il faut sélectionner le port USB sur lequel elle est branchée an allant dans Outils -> Port. C'est la partie un peu hasardeuse puisqu'il n'y a pas (à ma connaissance du moins) de moyen de savoir à coup duquel il s'agit. Il faudra essayer et voir si ça marche.

Pour finir flasher l'imprimante avec Croquis -> Téléverser
